  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Edmund Quincy says that the Dedham Female Anti-Slavery Society voted to transfer &quot;their auxiliaryship to the M. F. E. Soc. [Massachusetts Female Emancipation Society].&quot; The minority that has withdrawn is considering what course to take. Edmund Quincy considers it &quot;all important&quot; that Caroline Weston should be present at their meeting to help them, &quot;for their ignorance of business is extraordinary.&quot; Edmund Quincy wants Caroline Weston to come Friday evening and stay at his house through Sunday. He is glad to hear of Henry G. Chapman&apos;s convalescence. He recommends a hobby &quot;in the domain of Graham,&quot; which he considers as requiring vegetarianism to perfect it. In connection with his visit to Lynn, Edmund Quincy comments on &quot;the double-faced &amp; double-named Manford alias Colman.&quot; [Dr. Manford, alias John Colman, see William Lloyd Garrison, Vol. II, note 348.] Edmund Quincy describes a Whig celebration at Dedham in which ladies walked in a procession. Edmund Quincy remarks that &quot;the &apos;sphere of woman&apos; must be made of caoutchouc of the most elastic description.&quot;</subfield>
